Stopped at the

Stanton, Mott, Wright,
Davis, Wilbour, Gage
Brown (O.) Anthony -
Phelps,
Splendid audience

At one meal -
when our whole troup
were going to our table
in Dining room - Jessie
Benton Fremont - beckoned me
to her table - where only
She & the Gen. were - &

said in the brightest
shrewdest way - 'Now
-- tell Miss A. have
you hunted the country
over & picked out & brought
to Washington a score of
the most beautiful
women you could find -
and when I looked - I
replied - whether I hunted or
not - they are a very commanding
lot of women -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her trip to Washington National Convention, her visit to Arlington House, and a conversation with Jessie Benton Fremont.

Took cars at 7 A.M.
for Uniontown 72 miles
stopped at McLelland House
Had good audience
& everybody seemed
delighted
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony traveled to Uniontown, Pa, stopped at McLelland House, and had a good audience where everyone seemed delighted.

entries.fullText:
Uniontown till 1.30 P.M.
Had several gentlemen
callers - Rev's, Judges &
Lawyers -- no women
except two young
nieces of Mr. Heafwood
got 4 subscribers
& a $75 check

Arrived at Pittsburgh at
6 P.M. & early
to bed -- after writing
letters - to Peoria Ill -
and to P.P. at Home -
enclosing $80 --

Snowing & sleeting all
day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had several gentlemen callers in Uniontown, got 4 subscribers and a $75 check. She arrived in Pittsburgh and wrote letters to Peoria Ill and P.P. at Home.

entries.fullText:
Pittsburgh Pa -
Monongahela House
Room 22 -- fronting the
Monongahela River
If I can only give
the people what they
shall feel worthy as I
seemed to at Uniontown
is the burden of my hope
Mr. McLanahan
James C. Purdy
Had Large audience
[?] none save A.E.D's
Largest -- all seemed pleased
met [?] Smith
teacher
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stayed at the Monongahela House in Pittsburgh and had a large audience. She met Mr. McLanahan, James C. Purdy, and [?] Smith, a teacher.

entries.fullText:
-- Left on 9:45 A.M. Train
for Chicago by the Fort
Wayne [South?]au --
Rev. S. Aughey & wife
of Dacotah City Nebraska
on board -- Lutheran -- they
organized W. Suffrage up there
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Pittsburgh for Chicago on a train with Rev. S. Aughey and his wife, who organized Women's Suffrage in Dacotah City, Nebraska.

entries.fullText:
-- arrived
7 A.M. -- breakfasted at
Aunt Anne Eliza Dickinson's
& short good chat -- found
Judge Bradwell & wife -- They
evidently feel it necessary to
assure me of their friendliness --
-- They voted Illinois over to The
Cleveland Seceders -- Then
found S. M. Booth, -Miss
E. E. [So?ifies] the division
here is strong just [?] or,
- differ & divide -- So it
will be, so it is everywhere --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Chicago and has breakfast with Aunt Anne Eliza Dickinson. She meets with Judge Bradwell and his wife, who assure her of their friendliness. She also meets with S. M. Booth and Miss E. E. [So?ifies], who discuss the strong division in the area.

entries.fullText:
Peoria - Ill - $125
M.F. Kaufman -
Arrived 7 A.M. - Found Mr
K. to be a young German -
Bill Poster + Paper Distributor
attached to the office -
He called & paid down Cash
before evening - then brought a
high school scholar of 18 - Miss
Annis Ford of this City- Who
in a most dignified manner
introduced me to the audience
- She wants to study Law - &
her brain would do honor the
profession - Letters from
P .P. and sister Mary
Check $50 from sister
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Peoria, Illinois and met with M.F. Kaufman, a young German bill poster and paper distributor. She received cash payment and met a high school scholar named Miss Annis Ford who introduced her to the audience. She also received letters from P.P. and her sister Mary and a check from her sister.

entries.fullText:
Mattoon Ill.
Slept till near noon -
or laid in bed - Anna
left 1.40 for Indianapolis -
I slept a little & went to hall
at 8 to find 400 people
assembled - made a
good speech - all voted
for 16th Amendment -
Take 12.40 Train for Chicago -
C. B. Bostwick is
Chairman Com -

Entire receipts above
expenses $95.95 and
six subscribers
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony slept in Mattoon, Illinois until near noon and then went to a hall where she found 400 people assembled. She made a good speech and all voted for the 16th Amendment. She then took a train for Chicago. The entire receipts above expenses were $95.95 and six subscribers.

entries.fullText:
On account of smash
up of freight ahead
of us delayed 8 hours
- got into Chicago
just in time to
get on C. B. & Q. R. R.
and reach Earlville at
6:45. P.M. - found
cousin Susan at Depot
- had good meeting
$20 receipts
Staid at Grovers - like
Mrs. G. ever so much
found letters from
P.P. & home--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Earlville, IL after a delay due to a freight accident in Chicago. She had a good meeting and received $20 in receipts.

entries.fullText:
Spent this
day & night with
Cousin Susan
had good visit
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day and night with her cousin Susan in Earlville, IL and had a good visit.

Good audience
enthusiastic vote

entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Bloomington, Illinois where she met with D.A. Ray and spoke to a good audience who were enthusiastic about the 16th amendment.

Our young girls

entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony reports that Mrs. Stanton had a splendid audience at her Lyceum lecture in Peoria Ill, and mentions E. R. Brown and T. Cratty.

entries.fullText:
Peoria County Convention
Large and
enthusiastic
Albert J. Ingersol -
Whom I had never seen -
was present - The
Democratic Edition stated
laws for women
better than for men -
Mr Ingersol sent note
to President - don't let
Miss answer that fellow
I want to take him in hand -
& he showed case after case
in his practice - & wives whom
the people know - of the cruel
injustice to women - it was
a most splendid speech - I
have never heard it surpassed -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a Peoria County Convention where Albert J. Ingersol gives a splendid speech about the cruel injustice to women.

entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stopped at Cone's in Farmington Ill and had a small meeting despite the tremendous rain and mud with Luther Birge and Miss Maggie E. Cone.

entries.fullText:
stopped at Mr F Joys
Mrs Sutherland at Miss
Browns to tea -
small meeting - a
dark & rainy night
Had arranged for
a temperance lecture
Sunday night at Methodist
church -but the
minister Mr [Well?]

didn't like 25 cts. admission
fee - So gave
it up - though
(over)
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stopped at Mr F Joys and Mrs Sutherland's place in Elmwood Ill and had a small meeting despite the dark and rainy night with Mrs E.R. Brown. She also arranged for a temperance lecture at the Methodist church on Sunday night but it was cancelled due to the minister reporting that the brethren didn't like the 25 cents admission fee.

entries.fullText:
Dined & slept
with Mrs Pursell
her husband an old
Democrat -

It was clear the real
reason was that nothing
would be proved this
means for woman is
to help the moral
& religious work
forward -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony dined and slept with Mrs. Pursell, an old Democrat, in Elmwood, Illinois. She reflects on the role of women in moral and religious work.

entries.fullText:
Debated with Mr. P.
W. Wilcox a carpenter
Splendid audience
though terrifically
muddy & dark -
Stopped with
Mrs Smith - she
introduced me-
She is a Good Templar
enthusiastic to get the
ballot to stop Rum
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony debated with Mr. P. W. Wilcox, a carpenter, in Mendota, Illinois. She stayed with Mrs. Smith, a Good Templar who is enthusiastic about getting the ballot to stop rum.

entries.fullText: Stopped at John McCormicks - his wife Anna McCormick. Real old line Douglass Democrats - Splendid audience. Dreadfully muddy & dark. The good old Democrat introduced me much to the surprise & merriment of his friends - richest man in town - (a real Irishman is [?])
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits John McCormick in La Saille, Illinois and speaks to a splendid audience of real old line Douglass Democrats.

entries.fullText: School Hall - stopped at Mr F. H. Buck - current woman - Mrs. John Burnham Dr. R. J. Patterson of Insane Asylum - Terrible storm. Small audience.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Batavia, Illinois and speaks to a small audience at School Hall amidst a terrible storm.

entries.fullText:
Peoria Ill -- Debate with Prof. E.C. Hewett of State Normal University, at Normal managed by D.A. Ray - Bloomington

Andierrer[?] Irmolt[?] - Very[?] stormy[?] - Just as I knew - Peoria is surfeited already -
entries.summaryText: Debate with Prof. E.C. Hewett of State Normal University in Normal, managed by D.A. Ray in Peoria, Illinois. Stormy weather. Mentions Andierrer[?] Irmolt[?].

entries.fullText: Peoria Ill - Record evening debate with Prof H Curet[?] Audience still smaller The Prof. no spirit. don't draw fire at all -- Dined at 3 P.M. with Mrs Rv. Re. Phelps - Pleasant chat with [?]al. Re[?]ly Ingersal - he promises to be at May meeting [and he was - The R????t?? Editor made statement that Laws for women had better ?t?? for men --
entries.summaryText: Record evening debate with Prof H Curet[?] in Peoria, Illinois. Dined with Mrs Rv. Re. Phelps and had a pleasant chat with [?]al. Re[?]ly Ingersal. The R????t?? Editor made a statement about laws for women.

entries.fullText:
D.A. Ray -- Manager --
Had good 10 A.M., at
Gilman -- Beefsteak, eggs,
dry toast & coffee -- Met on
[?] Mass Jennie Alexander
of Eugene - Ind. going to C,
to hear me - her father Wm
Alexander - Sen.-- always taught
her to believe in women's suffrage
-- a beautiful noble blonde --
more resembling niece Ann
Eliza, than any face I ever
saw -- specially the mouth --
Arrived at 2 P.M.. to my
utter dismay found no
night train to Chicago -- So no
meeting with Mrs. Stanton tomorrow --
entries.summaryText: Met with D.A. Ray and Jennie Alexander in Champaign, IL. Jennie is a supporter of women's suffrage and resembles Ann Eliza. Was disappointed to find out there was no night train to Chicago to meet with Mrs. Stanton.

[Sherman House - Chicago

Oh No -- The
-- R.R. House

all the day -- Spoke
on moral power of

entries.summaryText: Spent the day at the R.R. House in Champaign, IL. Spoke about the moral power of the ballot in the evening.

entries.dateText:
APRIL
4 Monday
[Sturgis - Mich
J. G. Waite]
entries.fullText:
Spent day in
Chicago - Met
Mrs. Stanton at North
Western Depot a few
minutes -
talked over
the Theodore Tilton
amnesty & Union proposition
- neither believe
Boston will concede
an iota -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day in Chicago and met with Mrs. Stanton and J. G. Waite to discuss the Theodore Tilton amnesty and Union proposition, but they do not believe Boston will concede.

entries.dateText:
APRIL
5 Tuesday
Sturgis Mich --
J.G. Waite
entries.fullText:
Arrived at
noon --
Stopped with
the Waite's --
Said hundreds
were in Monday night
from counties round
about -- but couldn't
come again this --
Change of time or
place always bad --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Sturgis, Michigan and stayed with J.G. Waite. They discussed the difficulty of getting people to attend events due to changes in time or location.

entries.fullText:
M. Winsten Baxter -
wife a niece [daughter] of
Sally Holly's - Stopped
with them - home elegant
and every way hospitable -

Here the women
have organized themselves
with a "Phalanx" and
prosecute Rum sellers -
shut up all shops but one -
Thursday A.M. before going
to Jonesville - organized
them into a W. S. Society
with Mrs. Hogarth Pres.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Jonesville, Michigan and stays with M. Winsten Baxter and Sally Holly's daughter. She observes the women in the town have organized themselves into a 'Phalanx' to prosecute rum sellers and shut down all shops but one. Before leaving, she organizes them into a W.S. Society with Mrs. Hogarth as President.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. W. R. Harglett
(Mrs Stanton at Iowa City) -
Stopped at Hotel -
Mrs. Hargglett introduced
me - good meeting
in Baptist Church -
Mrs. H is beginning
to speak on W.S.
has fine appearance
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Hillsdale, Michigan and stays at a hotel. She meets Mrs. W. R. Harglett who introduces her to a good meeting at the Baptist Church. Mrs. Harglett is beginning to speak on W.S. and has a fine appearance.

entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stopped with Miss T. at Mr. Burton Kents in Adrian - Mich. Audience small. entries.fullText:
Ms C. L. Case
Mrs. J. Mabbett Brown
met me at Napoleon
Station to take me to her
house - Mrs claimed me --
quite a new feature
to have people quarrel
is to have [?] have

Good audience &
enthusiastic vote for
16th Amendment --
At close - Grandfather
Reads brother Ben's
son Benjamin revealed himself

daughters with him --
Mrs Conable -- Pres. W.S.A.

entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was met by Ms C. L. Case and Mrs. J. Mabbett Brown at Napoleon Station to take me to her house. Good audience & enthusiastic vote for 16th Amendment. At close - Grandfather Reads brother Ben's son Benjamin revealed himself to me -- wife & three daughters with him -- Mrs Conable -- Pres. W.S.A. introduced.

entries.fullText:
In P. M. Mr & Mrs.
Hulbert Perine -- called
for me to go their house
to Mother's Cousin Benjamin
Read -- son of Uncle
Ben. Read -- he looks a
good deal as Grandfather
Read used to - - called
at evening at Mrs. C. Loretti Case
& met a large number of friends --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mr. and Mrs. Hulbert Perine and Mother's Cousin Benjamin Read in Jackson, Michigan. She also visits Mrs. C. Loretti Case and meets a large number of friends.

entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mr. Bradley and Mr. E. D. North, students of Albion College, and attends a lecture with about 300 people in Albion, Michigan.

Joseph & Lydia Lapham -
Robert Baker - Breedsville
-Mich - Son of
Reuben Baker - Easton

30 miles to see & hear me -
The stories pretty
thoroughly Clevelandized -
Small audience

(Mrs Stanton – Hudson – B. [P])
Small audience – price
reduced to 25 cts - so only $10.
Dined at the beautiful
farm house of The Browns. 14
miles up The River – seemed
So like our old farm home –
– spent night with Sarah
Jane Hyatt - now wife of
Ed. C. Nichols – four beautiful
children – very happy – husband
10 years younger – splendid
young man - Threshing machine
-Splendid business
Beautiful evening –
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony dined with Mr. Jeremiah Brown and spent the night with Sarah Jane Hyatt and her family.

Beautiful daughter Nellie
