entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a preliminary meeting of the National W. Suffrage Association at the Parlors of the Woman's Bureau.

entries.fullText:
National W. Sufferage
Association
E. Cady Stanton Pres.
Appollo Hall
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a meeting of the National Women's Suffrage Association at Appollo Hall in New York, where Elizabeth Cady Stanton was the president.

entries.fullText:
Brooklyn Equal Rights
anniversary meeting
at the Academy of
Music at evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the Brooklyn Equal Rights anniversary meeting at the Academy of Music in Brooklyn.

entries.fullText:
American Equal
Rights Association met
at Mrs M E Winchesters &
voted itself into the
5th AvenueTilton Union
movement - only
Lucy Stone & husband
dissenting -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting of the American Equal Rights Association at Mrs M E Winchesters and votes for the 5th AvenueTilton Union movement. Lucy Stone and her husband are the only dissenters.

entries.fullText:
Brooklyn - at Cousin
Samantha's - Lapham's
called at Tilton's, Moulton
called with carriage - TT
& self rode to Prospect
Park - after dinner
at Cousins went over
to N.Y. office & with
Miss Paddleton mailed
several hundred
envelopes with
tickets for Mrs Houtons
lecture to Ladies [?]
to Teachers & Revolution
subscribers - after
dusk went into all
the morning editorial
[?]
Ms S. [Lester?]
on ? McFarland Richard
son [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day in Brooklyn, visiting Cousin Samantha's and riding to Prospect Park. She also mails tickets for Mrs Houton's lecture and visits the N.Y. office with Miss Paddleton. In the evening, she goes into all the morning editorial [?].

entries.fullText:
Am working w/
the women alon
meeting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is working with a group of women in a meeting.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Stantons lecture
on the Mc-Farland /
Richardson case
at Apollo Hall to
Ladies [?]
Large audience -
half complimentary -
Made [?] of
fact at close - & said
any ladies visiting to
help out [explaining?] work
[?? ??] notes at
platform - & a good
deal more than
enough was thus
left
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a lecture by Mrs. Stanton on the Mc-Farland/Richardson case at Apollo Hall with a large audience of women. Mrs. Stanton encourages any visiting ladies to help out with the work and leaves notes at the platform.

entries.fullText:
Slept at Theo. Tiltons—
Lunched with R. J. Johnston
& R. P. Mr. &
Mrs. Curtis, Mrs.
Ballard & Tilton &
Streetwell & self
all went up to 15th St. &
Broadway & congregated at
Parlors for Union W. S. Society
they decided to take
Revolution off my
hands
Took 7.20 train
for Hornellsville
entries.summaryText: Slept at Theo. Tiltons, went to Union W. S. Society meeting.

entries.fullText:
Hornellsville Steuben Co,
N.Y. - arrived at 8.45
A.M. Mrs. Ted Brown of
Owego took me to her
friend Mrs. M. E. Browns
had pleasant quarters -
discussion with Mr
Bennis - a Lawyer -
packed house & lively
time
entries.summaryText: Arrived in Hornellsville, had discussion with Mr. Bennis.

entries.fullText:
May
20 Friday

entries.dateText:
May
23 Monday
Wellsville Allegany Co. N.Y.
entries.fullText:
May
23 Monday
Wellsville Allegany Co. N.Y.
Arrived at 9.45 A.M.
Stopped at Wm. A. Baldwins
Frank F. Hamilton
sister of Mrs. Baldwin
Letter from Lib B
Very rainy P.M.
Mr. Fish sec'y of
Lecture Com
Took train at 10,
left Mr. Dennis closing
up the debate -
Trunk not at Depot—
Mr Fish promised to
double check it through
the roughest, hardest shaking
I ever took on sleeping car.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Wellsville, Allegany Co. N.Y. and stayed at Wm. A. Baldwin's. She received a letter from Lib B and met with Mr. Fish, the secretary of the Lecture Committee. She took a train at 10 PM and experienced a rough ride on the sleeping car. Her trunk was not at the depot but Mr. Fish promised to double check it through.

entries.fullText:
Judge Tilden -
160 Euclid st.,
Missed A.M. Connection,
so spent the
day in Cleveland -
Called on Mrs.
Tilden - She was very
glad to get explanation
of Boston, Cleveland, Lucy
movement - got pass
to Chicago through Mr
Hudson of The Leader
letter -
Took train at
6.30 for Chicago - Phebe
Couzens on Palace
Car - I shared her
section - had pleasant
trip - two Brooklyn men
on board & Camden C. Dike
138 Columbia st - & H. B. Hawk
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day in Cleveland, visits Mrs. Tilden, and gets a pass to Chicago through Mr. Hudson of The Leader letter. She then takes a train to Chicago with Phebe Couzens and shares her section with her.

entries.fullText:
Chicago - Breakfasted at
the Fremont House -
& H. B. Hawkins - No.
90 Joralemon St. Brooklyn -
Convention
opened small - Dr.
L. C. Blake - 876 Prairie Av. -
in the Chair - next
ran naught to
Tenard Jones
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a small convention in Chicago, where Dr. L. C. Blake is in the chair and Tenard Jones is mentioned.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Warren - Mrs Loomis sister
827 State St - near 16th
Judge Broadwater - 111 Mich. Av.
Office 82 Washington St.
The Convention larger
Geo. F. train for the
first time since the
Kansas Campaign came
into this evening session
& I introduced him.
Staid at Sherman
House - Dr. Keckler - Cin -
Mr & Mrs Hazlett
Mich. & G. F. T. supped together
Mrs Hazlett the President
of the North Western W.S.A.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her day in Chicago, including meeting with various people and introducing Geo. F. train at the Convention.

entries.fullText:
Judge Waite & wife called
at Sherman - talked
but nothing fixed even
in thought -
Went to my Aunts &
finished - then slept
till 6 P.M. - then
went to Woman's
House & spoke to
a full house - then
home, with Mr Brooks
& staid & all night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Judge Waite and his wife, speaks at a full house, and spends the night with Mr. Brooks.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Harriet Brooks several calls - among
them Mrs. Packard -
who has been in insane
asylum for years,
because of unbelief
in Orthodoxy - her
husband a minister
Called at Loomis, Mr
Jones, Dr. Blakes - then
about trunk - no clue
to it - then to Briggs House
to drive with Mr Brooks -
then telegram to Wellsville
to find when & how trunk
was checked - Then to
Farwell Hall for meeting
nobody there then to Judge
Waites office - then to Mrs.
Loomis Sisters, Mrs. Warrens -
41 Birthday of twin brothers -
then home with Mrs S.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony makes several calls, including one to Mrs. Packard who has been in an insane asylum for years due to her unbelief in Orthodoxy. She also goes to various locations to find a lost trunk and attends a meeting at Farwell Hall.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. E. C Loomis tooke
me to Rev Colliers Church
Dearborn St - North side-
-I dined with the Colliers
Cordial - but coolly told
me women had better
wait 20 years for the
ballot than accept,
recognize or endorse
Geo. F. [Drain?] as an advocate -
my reply - "You
are not a woman" caused
him to say "hear me through"
Mrs Rebecca Mott called
& took me to tea with her
girls - 252 Oak st -
north side - at eve
went to Aunt A. E. Ds.
found all well -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends church with Mrs. E. C Loomis and dines with the Colliers. She also has a conversation with Geo. F. [Drain?] about women's suffrage and has tea with Mrs. Rebecca Mott and her girls.

entries.fullText:
Aunt A. E. D. - washed
my Linen—through &
through—starched &
ironed & left for Depot
Central Illinois at 11.30—
Lunched at C. B. Waites'—
Hyde Park—Mrs. W. came
up with me at 5 P.M,
got Telegram answer from Wellsville
saying my trunk was
sent by express to Sherman
House—cost $1.75—
Took tea & slept at
Dr. S. C. Blakes—Several
friends called in evening—
Judge Waites important
business, dwindled into
thin air—There really seems
to be no executive ability—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Central Illinois, has lunch at C. B. Waites' in Hyde Park, and spends the night at Dr. S. C. Blakes'.

entries.fullText:
Dr. S. C. Blakes—to breakfast—
Mrs. F. Jones took Mrs. B.
and self to Sherman
House—found trunk &
had it doubly marked—it
was sent by express to
Sherman House—
Lunched at Judge Bradwells.
Mrs. B. ill—
Then went to Aunt
A. E. D's—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony retrieves her trunk from Sherman House and has lunch at Judge Bradwells before visiting Aunt A. E. D's.

entries.fullText: At A.E.Ds. - beautiful day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent a beautiful day at A.E.Ds. in Chicago, Ill.

entries.fullText:
Dined at Cousin
Hannahs - then
went to F. Jones
& slept - 910 Prarie Av
Gen Osborn of Chicago
Skidmore of NY. City
and Judge Bond
of Baltimore called
at Jones - Bond
not a solid man
as I had supposed -
went to M. E.
Strawberry Festival
in evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony dined at Cousin Hannahs, then slept at F. Jones' house. Gen Osborn, Skidmore, and Judge Bond visited Jones, but Anthony found Bond to not be a solid man. Later, Anthony went to the M. E. Strawberry Festival in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Mr & Mrs Fernando
Jones drove up with
carriage and stopped - to
dinner with Mrs R.
Somers -

Had large audience
Methodist Church -
President E. O. Haven
introduced me - &
endorsed woman suffrage.
Mr Hughes gave
$10,000 to build Hall
for University girls
to have free rooms -
girls admitted to
to university on equal
terms-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had dinner with Mr & Mrs Fernando Jones and Mrs R. Somers in Evanston, Illinois. She spoke at the Methodist Church to a large audience and was introduced by President E. O. Haven who endorsed woman suffrage. Mr Hughes gave $10,000 to build a hall for University girls to have free rooms.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Somers called
with me on President
Haven at his room
in college- splendid
grounds- then came
to city- dined at the
Richmond- Got Pass
on C.B. & Q. Rail Road
- Parasol from Express
office- letters from E.C.
Browne about new regime
- Cook Co. W.S. meeting in
P.M. - then Aunt A.E.'s
a nap, dressing ruffled silk
supper & with cousin
Melissa to George
Scoville's- 260 Warren Av -
to Reception- goodly number
there- Handsome
purse presented by Judge
Waite & thanks returned by
S.B.A.- slept at Cousin H.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony met with Mrs. Somers and President Haven at his room in college. She got a pass on C.B. & Q. Rail Road and a parasol from the express office. She attended a Cook Co. W.S. meeting and then went to a reception at George Scoville's where she was presented with a handsome purse by Judge Waite.

entries.fullText:
Breakfasted Cousin
Hannah D. Doyles -
packed trunk - dined
wrote letters and slept at
Aunt A. E. D's.
entries.summaryText: Breakfasted with Cousin Hannah D. Doyles, packed trunk, wrote letters, and slept at Aunt A. E. D's.

entries.fullText: Mrs. E. A. Kennedy _
entries.summaryText: Met with Mrs. E. A. Kennedy in Sandwich, Ill.

entries.fullText:
JUNE
7 Tuesday

JUNE
8 Wednesday
Indianapolis
Mrs. Walker -- 66
Christian - Av -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Walker, aged 66, was in Indianapolis on June 8th with a person named Christian at Av.

entries.fullText: Annual meeting -10th
entries.summaryText: Annual meeting on the 10th in Indianapolis, Indiana State.

entries.fullText: Henry M. Rice, Alma T. Rice Seeing Mrs. Col. James Thompson, Prof. Richard Owen, Dr. Mott- Pres. College, Indiana State University, Prof. E.P. Cole-, Hon. D.W. Vorhees of Terra Haute Ind. going to speak tomorrow
entries.summaryText: Meeting with various people in Bloomington, Indiana including Henry M. Rice, Alma T. Rice, Mrs. Col. James Thompson, Prof. Richard Owen, Dr. Mott- Pres. College, Prof. E.P. Cole-, Hon. D.W. Vorhees, who will speak tomorrow.

entries.fullText:
At Mr H. M. Rice
Calls from Prof. Cole -
student W. R. Houghton
- college boys at public
exercises ridiculed woman
suffrage - Prof. Owen &
Riebult rebuked them
Hon D. W. Voorhes
spoke on Court House
commons - showed
up special legislation
for negroes - thereby
showed the power of
ballot-

Then at 3 P.M. went
to Crawfordsville
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Bloomington and attends a public exercise where college boys ridicule woman suffrage. Hon D. W. Voorhes spoke on Court House commons and showed the power of ballot. Then she went to Crawfordsville.

entries.fullText:
Rained all day -
Went to Tempe -
[?] meeting
in P.M. and
made little talk
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting in Tempe and makes a little talk. It rained all day.

entries.fullText:
constant string
of calls all the day
and teas at Dr.
Wilhites -who has
a successful practice
in C. -
Good audience
- largest for a long
time
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day in Crawfordsville, Indiana with Miss Lizzie M. Boynton and Dr. Wilhites. She receives many calls and attends teas. She speaks to a good audience.

people: Mr and Mrs T. A. Bland
entries.fullText:
J. C. McPherson
notice that the way
was not open- so
went to Indianapolis
Spent two hours called
on Mr and Mrs T. A.
Bland - then on
to Muncie Ind -
the home of the Wilson
Family -
Mary Thomas Clark
Lecturer - Chesterfield
Madison Co. Ind
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Indianapolis and then to Muncie, Indiana. She visits Mr. and Mrs. T. A. Bland and the Wilson Family. She attends a lecture by Mary Thomas Clark in Chesterfield, Madison County.

entries.fullText:
- Convention postponed
on account of Church
Festivals gotten up
seemingly to conflict
also illness of some of
the prominent friends
Spoke this evening to a good
audience
Muncie Ind
Mrs. Jane C. Hunter
daughter of Osborn
Wilson - Centre Falls
Washington Co. N. Y.
Here, too, are Valery
Wilson - Elizabeth Wilson
Waite & Kate Whiffle
Kirby - daughter of
Maria Wilson -
entries.summaryText: Convention postponed due to Church Festivals and illness of some friends. Spoke to a good audience. Visited Muncie, IN and met with Mrs. Jane C. Hunter and others.

entries.cityOrState:
Monticello - Ill - Seven miles
from Bernent Station on
Toledo, W&W. R. R - just below
Tolono - on Ill. Central -

Muncie Ind.
entries.fullText:
at Levi Hunter's
A great many
called - good
meeting -
John A. Wilson (son of [?])
Boonville Cooper Co. Mr.
Jason Wilson - Marion - Ind
Osborn Wilson Aurora - Ill -
Rufus Wilson - Union City Ind
Gilbert Wilson - Marian, Ind
Took train for
Green Castle at 12. night
entries.summaryText: Visited Levi Hunter's and had a good meeting. Met with several people including John A. Wilson, Jason Wilson, Osborn Wilson, Rufus Wilson, and Gilbert Wilson. Took train for Green Castle at midnight.

entries.fullText:
Bloomington Ind—
[[M?] Ind]
Mrs. Jane Wilson Hunt
Dined at Volney
Wilson's Took tea
at Dr. Samuel
Anthony's—85 years old
Son Edwin C. Anthony
Spoke at evening —
good audience—but
only 90 cts admission &
Hall rent $10—so
from both nights only $15.80
The above belongs to Thursday—
Bloomington Ind
had large meeting—
Prof. Rich. Owen & wife
at Tea at Mr Rices—
$32
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was in Bloomington, Indiana on June 17th, 1870. She dined with Mrs. Jane Wilson Hunt, took tea at Dr. Samuel Anthony's, and spoke at an evening event. She mentions the admission fee and hall rent for the event. She also had a large meeting with Prof. Rich. Owen and his wife at Mr. Rice's.

entries.fullText:
Bloomington Ind
Mrs. N. M. Rice
College Chapel last night
All invited to
dinner at C. P.
Tuleys—Prof Owen
& wife—Mr & Mrs Rice.
Took train at 3 P.M,
two hours at Lafayette
Depot—So tired I
actually slept on
soft side of bench
with no cushion—&
no pillow but water
proof—
entries.summaryText: On June 18th, 1870, Susan B. Anthony was in Bloomington, Indiana. She attended a dinner at C. P. Tuleys with Mrs. N. M. Rice, Prof Owen, and Mr. & Mrs. Rice. She also mentions taking a train and sleeping on a bench with no cushion or pillow.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Chicago [??]
at 6.30—found
Mrs Bradwell worse—
probably cancer of
— & fatal—if so—
breakfasted there—
then to Mrs Loomis'
had a napp & a
wash and dinner
then Mrs. L. called
with me at Mrs. Jones
and Mrs Goodings
& Clarks— then I
went Aunt A. E. D's &
found her gone to
Cousin Susan's & Uncle
Johns with Uncle
Abram Anthony—
took bread & milk dripping
& black raspberries—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Chicago and visits Mrs. Bradwell, Mrs. Loomis, Mrs. Jones, Mrs. Goodings, Clarks, Aunt A. E. D, Cousin Susan, Uncle Johns, and Uncle Abram Anthony.

entries.fullText:
Called at Judge
Waites Offices & found
he had left letters of
Richmond House—
Wasn't able to get
off on 10 Train to
Mendota—so stopped
at The Richmond &
read up the letters
I suppose it is for
the best that I gave up
The Revolution—but
it will seem pretty
tough to see it fall so
below its old standard—
At 4.20 left for Earlville—
Went to A. P. Groves.
Mrs. G's hands full work
three months baby & lame
husband—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Judge Waites' office and reads letters at The Richmond before leaving for Earlville to visit A. P. Groves and his family.

entries.fullText:
Woke up with severe
pain before daylight
rushed out & out & and
again until it turned
to dysentery form & I
began to feel that to
lay flat on the back
was my only way on get
So I vomited clear
bile with each sun
& really scared - at
4 P. M. got up bathed &
dressed though I actually
hadn’t strength to stand
up. Pillsbury Came at
noon from Peoria &
Elmwood— took a cup
of tea & juice of beef - & at
7 [?], the son took [Azelri?]
R. & self out to farm—Cou
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony woke up with severe pain before daylight and rushed out until it turned to dysentery form. She vomited clear bile with each sun and was really scared. She got up at 4 P.M. and dressed though she actually hadn’t strength to stand up. Pillsbury came at noon from Peoria and Elmwood and took a cup of tea and juice of beef.

entries.fullText:
Said in bed
till after noon- then
bathed & dressed but
felt pretty staggering-
Ate only porridge
until 7 P.M. then
a cup of tea
7 a bit of bread
& butter & strawberries-
venturesome- but did it
Cousin Susan arrived
last night- had been
to Uncle John Anthonys
with Uncle Abram &
Aunt Ann Eliza D?
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stayed in bed till after noon and then bathed and dressed but felt pretty staggering. She ate only porridge until 7 P.M. then a cup of tea, 7 a bit of bread and butter and strawberries. Cousin Susan arrived last night and had been to Uncle John Anthonys with Uncle Abram and Aunt Ann Eliza D?

entries.fullText:
Very hot—feeling better
Walked over to Halley
Hoxies—Aunt Hannahs
son Ira's oldest son—
found his wife a bright
and nice appearing little
woman—with two children
and not yet 22 years old
Dined on rice & milk
then I slept two hours or
more on longue—then
chatted then scribbled
an letter to mother
entries.summaryText: Susan visits Halley Hoxies and Aunt Hannahs, meets Ira's oldest son's wife and writes a letter to her mother.

entries.fullText:
Left Cousin Susan's
at 7 A.M. with son Eddy
in big waggon & went
to M. on Freight Train—
Awfully hot—went to
Mrs Smiths —
A. P. Grover, Cousin
Susan & Parker Pillsbury
arrived at M. about
noon—a great fire
in the night destroyed
a whole block—The
meeting very small—
both P.M. & Evening
entries.summaryText: Susan leaves Cousin Susan's and attends a small convention in Mendota, where a fire destroyed a whole block.

entries.fullText:
Audiences still
very small—at
evening much larger—
P. P. & Grover left at
3 P.M.—P. P. to speak
at Earlville Sunday
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about small audiences in Mendota, Illinois, which grew larger in the evening. P. P. and Grover left at 3 P.M. and P. P. is scheduled to speak at Earlville on Sunday.

entries.fullText:
Terrifically hot—
Spoke on Temperance
in the Baptist Church
at 4 P.M. Some
400 persons present—
Minister opened
with Prayer & introduced
me—
Mr & Mrs Smith
took me three miles out
to call on Prudence
Crandall Phileo
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks on Temperance to a crowd of 400 people at the Baptist Church in Mendota, Illinois. She is introduced by the minister and later visits Prudence Crandall Phileo with Mr. and Mrs. Smith.

entries.fullText:
Left at 1 P.M.,
for Leavenworth Kan
entries.summaryText: Mendola M left for Leavenworth Kan.

entries.fullText:
JULY
1 Friday
Leavenworth

JULY
2 Saturday
Leavenworth
Mrs Johnson
The Post Master
called in A. M.
Sister A. & Maud
& self took tea
at Nicholas Smiths
-D.R. came for us
pleasant visit -
Mrs Smith is a
woman of great cul
ture - Mrs Gray
there also
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and her sister and friend had tea at Nicholas Smiths' house in Leavenworth. They had a pleasant visit with Mrs. Smith, who is a woman of great culture. Mrs. Johnson and The Post Master also visited in the morning, and Mrs. Gray was there as well.

entries.fullText:
Excessively hot
went to hear
Unitarian Minister
from St. Joseph
preach in the
evening
entries.summaryText: Attended a Unitarian sermon in Leavenworth.

entries.fullText:
Hot day. D. R. and
Arthur went to the
Fort- Aaron and self
didn’t go out—
At evening Mr.
Taylor of Wyandotte
called
entries.summaryText: Stayed indoors on a hot day, while some friends visited in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Heavy Thunder
Shower in P.M.
which cooled the air.
entries.summaryText: A heavy thunderstorm occurred in Leavenworth on July 5th, followed by a shower in the afternoon which cooled the air.

geographicalLocations: Mrs. C. I. H. Nichol farm home
entries.fullText:
Leavenworth—to Wyandott
Sister Annie
took me down town—
in A.M. Got Lace
Bonnet $10.50—French
Corsets $5. & c.
Took [Cons?] at 3 P.M.
brother D. R. went to
Depot with me—
Took tea at Mr
Taylors & then rode
out to Mrs. C. I. H. Nichol
farm home—2 miles—
with Mrs Spencer —Mrs
Root's sister—found
Mrs. N. alone & very
glad to see me—She
has two sons married—one
living on a [?] farm
adjoining hers—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes shopping and visits Mrs. C. I. H. Nichol's farm home in Wyandott.

geographicalLocations: Mrs. C. I. H. Nichols' farm home
entries.fullText:
Wyandott—[???] at
Mrs. C. I. H. Nichols' farm
home—snug & comfortable
—has 75 chickens—49
acres—worth $100 per acre
Mrs. N. walked to
town with me—dined
at Mrs. Taylors with
Mrs Frances Root—After
Dinner Mr Taylor went
with me to Kansas City—
to see Major Henning to
try for Pass to Fort Scott
& return—he was out,
so left a note asking
the courtesy & for tickets
if granted to be left
with ticket seller—
Mr Cook—a lawyer—
spent evening—& Mrs J. Left
called on Mrs Root—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mrs. C. I. H. Nichols' farm home and goes to Kansas City to try to get a pass to Fort Scott.

entries.fullText: Went to Kansas City in Hack—found Free Pass to Fort Scott & return - with Ticket Teller Arrived at 7.20 P.M. Both J. M. at Depot - raining fast - Found Mary, Lucy E. & Dan[?] all well & very comfortably situated - children grown ever so much - Met on Train C. D. Wilber of Wilmington, Ill—whom I met on Ill. Central R. last March - lame man - also Dr. S. D. Bowker of Kansas City - and Col. T. H. Board of Greenpsburg - Ken.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Fort Scott, Kansas from Kansas City and meets several people on the train.
Susan B. Anthony writes nothing on this day.

entries.fullText:
JULY
13 Wednesday
Fort Scott

JULY
14 Thursday
Fort Scott-
Spoke in City
Hall. Small
audience very
very hot. Double
headed girl on
exhibition. Circus
in town.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke in City Hall to a small audience in Fort Scott, where a double-headed girl was on exhibition and a circus was in town. The weather was very hot.

entries.fullText:
JULY
15 Friday
Fort Scott

entries.dateText:
JULY
16 Saturday
Fort Scott
Merritt, Mary
entries.fullText:
JULY
16 Saturday
Fort Scott
Merritt, Mary
and self took tea
at Millingtons. Rev.
Mr. Taylor, Rev. Mr.
Gardiner & wife &
others after tea.
many more called
Spoke again
this evening in the
M. E. Church to
about 100.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had tea with Merritt, Mary, Rev. Mr. Taylor, Rev. Mr. Gardiner and others at Millingtons and spoke again in the M. E. Church to about 100 people.

entries.fullText:
Rode out
north east of town
three miles with
Merritt in A.M.
to carry sewing
machine to a
Missouri widow
woman—Merritt
is very reticent—Still
gleaned many things
Spoke on Temperance
—especially woman's part in
the crime & cure
in M.E. Church to
a crowded house—
entries.summaryText: Rode out with Merritt to carry a sewing machine to a Missouri widow woman, spoke on Temperance in M.E. Church.

entries.fullText:
Fort Scott—Went
over to town—but
getting no word from
Paola—decided to
stop over another
day—Mary set
to work on my skirt & Dollie's
dress—
4 P.M. Mail
bro't letter from
Olathe of meeting
there the 20th—what
decided me to stay
on till Wednesday—
Ordered a nice
Lounge bedstead for
Dollie & Dannie—price
$20.
entries.summaryText: Went to town but decided to stay another day, Mary worked on skirts, received a letter about a meeting in Olathe, ordered a bedstead for Dollie and Dannie.

entries.fullText:
Spent the
day sewing or
rather fixing &
basting for M[??]
to sew on machine
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day sewing and fixing clothes for someone named M[??] to sew on a machine.
Susan B. Anthony wrote a journal entry on July 22nd, 1870 from Leavenworth.

entries.fullText:
July
23 Saturday
Leavenworth

July
24 Sunday
Leavenworth
Went to hear
Joel Moody—
back to R.R. Office
entries.summaryText: Went to hear Joel Moody and back to R.R. Office.

entries.fullText:
Left Leavenworth
at 8.15 A.M. for
Saratoga Springs—
very hot— at
Quincy terrifically hot—
took Sleeping Car
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Leavenworth for Saratoga Springs, stopping at Quincy where it was 'terrifically hot'.

entries.fullText:
Saratoga Springs
Arrived Albany
6 A.M.—Called
at Phebe Jones found
Margaret
Jones very feeble
with Consumption—
had cup of coffee
then left for Saratoga
at 7.10—Mrs Hazlett,
Mrs Blake, Mrs Gage
Olympia Brown there
full house in A.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Saratoga Springs from Albany and visited Phebe Jones, finding Margaret Jones very feeble with consumption. She then left for Saratoga and met with Mrs. Hazlett, Mrs. Blake, Mrs. Gage, and Olympia Brown.

entries.fullText:
Saratoga Springs
Good audiences
May Caldwell Warre
at Congress Hall-
Prof Davies
at Congress Hall
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about good audiences and mentions May Caldwell Warre and Prof Davies at Congress Hall in Saratoga Springs.

entries.fullText:
Saratoga Springs
All left [?]
Mrs Harglett & self at
8 A.M.- We walked
about town She left
at 1 P.M. at 3:45 I
left for Albany found
Margaret Jones still
more feeble- took tea
at Lydia Motts - &
took 11 train to Rochester.
Found P.W. Davis
& three young ladies on
board. Stopped
off at Rome
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her travels from Saratoga Springs to Rome, mentioning various people and locations along the way.

entries.fullText:
Arrived at
9:10 A. M. from Albany
Mr. Sheldon invited
me to breakfast with him
at Borgen Hall - Then
called at Army Posts
talked over all matter
Got home at 12 - noon
found all at church
Lane Mather
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Rochester from Albany and had breakfast with Mr. Sheldon at Borgen Hall. She then visited Army Posts and talked over all matter. She got home at noon and found all at church.

entries.fullText:
Sent letter & check
of $ 50 to Wier Carey
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony sent a letter and a check of $50 to Wier Carey.

entries.fullText:
Convention-
Expect failure
with Mrs Paulina
Wright Davis
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a convention in Niagra Falls with Mrs. Paulina Wright Davis and expects failure.

entries.fullText:
Mrs P. W. Davis
took me to various
points of interest &
footed bill-
entries.summaryText: Mrs. P. W. Davis takes Susan B. Anthony to various points of interest in Niagra Falls and pays for everything.

entries.fullText:
Sister Mary & self
took Erie Train at
2 P.M. for New York
dreadfully hot
entries.summaryText: Sister Mary and Susan B. Anthony took the Erie Train to New York, and it was dreadfully hot.

entries.fullText:
Arrived at Mrs
Murray at 7.30
A.M.- all natural
called at R.J.J.
and Brooklyn office
also the New York
office [?]
Revolution is
Mrs Williams
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived at Mrs. Murray's in New York at 7:30 AM and visited various offices. The Revolution is mentioned, as well as Mrs. Williams.

entries.fullText:
Went over
to Tenafly—
found all of
Mrs Stanton's children
home but
Neil—Daniel Cady—
& met a hearty
welcome—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Tenafly and met with Mrs. Stanton's children and Daniel Cady.

entries.fullText:
Long talks
over everything
& everybody—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had long talks about everything and everybody in Tenafly.

entries.fullText: Missed 9.45 train then rode down to Englewood & over to the Palisades - in Mrs Stanton's carriage she with us - took 11.30 train - & crossed to 20th st - took lunch with Mrs Murray & then down town - Grew cool at P.M.
entries.summaryText: Missed train, went to Englewood and Palisades with Mrs. Stanton, had lunch with Mrs. Murray and went downtown.

entries.fullText: To Brooklyn office then back to N.Y. suffrage rooms - 31 min after then to Mrs Phelps - found Mrs Davis gone - then to lunch at Mrs Murreys - then back to Brooklyn determined to go strait to Mrs Bullard - Studwell turned me back to Tenafly - arrived there at [?].30 - - long & late talk on state of woman suffrage affairs - demoralized enough - too much man influence
entries.summaryText: Went to Brooklyn office, suffrage rooms, Mrs. Phelps and Mrs. Murreys. Went to Brooklyn again and then to Tenafly to talk about woman suffrage affairs, demoralized by too much man influence.

entries.dateText:
August
14 Sunday
Nice & cool
Tenafly—N.J.—Mrs Stantons
I wrote letter Mrs Rose
Paris—France— —P. P. and
Mrs Griffing—Mrs S. wrote
calls for 2d Decade Meeting
entries.fullText:
August
14 Sunday
Nice & cool
Tenafly—N.J.—Mrs Stantons
I wrote letter Mrs Rose
Paris—France— —P. P. and
Mrs Griffing—Mrs S. wrote
calls for 2d Decade Meeting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about writing a letter to Mrs. Rose and Mrs. Stanton writing calls for 2d Decade Meeting. She also mentions Paris, France and P. P. and Mrs. Griffing.

entries.dateText:
August
19 Friday
Mrs Stanton came
over to Sarony's
& we sat for pictures
in all forms &
positions—dined
at 4th st. with
Mrs. Brown—Mrs
S. wrote letter to Mrs.
Tilton & I went to
Mrs Murrays & thence
to R. V. J's[?] & to the
Erie Depot for
Rochester —at 7:20
tired—beaten—
disgusted—But
with all business
matters settled &
arranged
entries.fullText:
August
19 Friday
Mrs Stanton came
over to Sarony's
& we sat for pictures
in all forms &
positions—dined
at 4th st. with
Mrs. Brown—Mrs
S. wrote letter to Mrs.
Tilton & I went to
Mrs Murrays & thence
to R. V. J's[?] & to the
Erie Depot for
Rochester —at 7:20
tired—beaten—
disgusted—But
with all business
matters settled &
arranged
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about sitting for pictures with Mrs. Stanton and dining with Mrs. Brown. She also mentions going to various locations and Mrs. S. writing a letter to Mrs. Tilton.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Rochester
11.10 A.M.—Seated
in Street Car found
my pocket book gone—
the beautiful red
turkey morocco one
sent me on my Fiftieth birthday
by Lucretia Mott—
only $3.50 in cash—Erie
R.R. Terminal has[?]—with
the one dollar Green
back received for the
transfer of The Revolution
to the Tilton, Curtis
Bullard Co.—So all
is gone—pocket must
have been picked—
Sister M & Self called
at Hallowells—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Rochester and discovered that her pocketbook, which contained a sentimental gift from Lucretia Mott, had been stolen.

entries.fullText:
Sunday—Cool—
remained at home
all day-
Sister Gula &
Aaron gone east
to Wash. Co. with
niece Maggie &
son Harry—Gula's
health very poor—her
lungs the trouble
Mother miserable
chiefly with new
setts of teeth—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stayed home while her sister and others went to Washington County. Her sister's health was poor and her mother was having trouble with her teeth.

entries.fullText:
Julia Datty came
to sister Hannah's
Brother D.R.'s third
child born this A.M,
at Leavenworth—
a boy—named
D.R.—born on his Papas birth day—
entries.summaryText: Julia Datty visits Hannah in Leavenworth and D.R.'s third child, a boy named D.R., is born on his father's birthday.

entries.fullText:
[Thomas Sherry
went home with
George E. Duke to stay
all night—going with
him to Spencerport today]
entries.summaryText: Thomas Sherry stays with George E. Duke and they plan to go to Spencerport together.

entries.fullText:
Amy Post called
in P.M. an hourr two—Seemed good
& old times like—
She begins to see
the lack of Phillips
& all me to act
speak or advise
in our movement
Julia Dutty lost
her pocket book this
P.M. in Street Car
Sister H. with her
utterly inexplicable
$30. in it
entries.summaryText: Amy Post visits and Julia Dutty loses her pocketbook.

entries.fullText:
Dr Allen & wife
called to see Mother
—teeth not right yet—
Letters from Mrs
Stanton—Lib. Brown
of New York—& Mrs
O. H. Spear of California
T. K.[?] went home
George Baker tonight
to go with him to
Spencerport tomorrow
Letter from Arthur
Mosher saying another
Anthony boy at Leavenworth
just in time
to run for Congress—
entries.summaryText: Dr. Allen visits and Susan receives letters from various people. Arthur Mosher informs Susan of another Anthony boy running for Congress.

entries.fullText:
Julia Batty left—
Catharine Willis called
entries.summaryText: Julia Batty left and Catharine Willis called.

entries.fullText:
Called at Frederick
Douglass—he gone
to Washington to see
about taking Editorship
of New Era—a
Colored peoples paper—
Miss Ossing there
talks as briskly as ever—
D. drying apples for
boys—all is Washington
—Rosa has four girls
Reading [L?]
entries.summaryText: Visited Frederick Douglass in Washington, who is considering taking the editorship of a colored people's paper called New Era. Miss Ossing was there and D was drying apples for the boys. Rosa has four girls reading.

entries.fullText:
Sister H. & self attended
Unitarian Church-
Mr Mann the preacher
more than ordinary-
sat with Mrs Marsh-
In P.M., Sister Mary and self called at
Jo. Curtiss - out riding-
then at Hallowells - out
riding with the Curtiss -
then, at Willis - at home
still reading Disraeli
Lothair - finished it
in evening- he makes
the most lovely,
strong & prevailing
character a liberal in
religion - Theodora
though in no sense a
propagandist makes
deeper impression than all
Cardinals, Bishops and Laymen
combined to carry him into
the Church—
entries.summaryText: Attended Unitarian Church, visited various places, and read Disraeli's Lothair.

entries.fullText:
Went to Dr. Allen’s with
Mother about her teeth
then went to 210
South Washington st,
Robert English & got my
pocket-book - lost Saturday
the 20th at Erie Depot — the
man found it Hon
Alfred Elys door yard
just over the fence
when morning - I can't
recal the possibility of
any person touching me,
that it was picked out
of pocket seems probable
else the money - 4.50 would
have been left in as well
as Erie Pass & Cards —
Shower in P.M.—
entries.summaryText: Went to the dentist with Mother and retrieved a lost pocketbook from Robert English.

entries.fullText: P. P. & Self called round to Amy Posts.
entries.summaryText: P. P. and Susan B. Anthony visited Amy Posts.

entries.fullText:
P.P. & self took tea
& spent evening at
Isaac Posts—Mary
& William Hallowell—
Elias & Mary Doty
there also— P.P.
gave one of his
best talks in the
evening—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had tea and spent the evening at Isaac Posts with P.P., Mary Hallowell, William Hallowell, Elias Doty, and Mary Doty. P.P. gave a talk in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Went to Depot with
P.P.—Train 2 hours
behind—decided to
wait night train—then
called at Mary Hallowells
and dined at Mrs
Blackalls—Mrs Watkeys
Niece—quite ill—
Then walked back
& P.P. decided to take
six train—got a
cup of tea at Amy Posts
Walked down depot again
train an hour behind—
then P.P. walked up
to Madison st. & then
returned—Suppose he
got off this time.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to the Depot with P.P. but the train was 2 hours behind, so they decided to wait for the night train. They visited Mary Hallowells and dined at Mrs. Blackalls. Mrs. Watkeys' niece was quite ill. P.P. decided to take the six train and got a cup of tea at Amy Posts. The train was an hour behind, and P.P. walked up to Madison st. and then returned. It is unclear if he got off this time.

entries.fullText:
SEPTEMBER
7 Wednesday

SEPTEMBER
8 Thursday
Spent A. M. in
pursuit of Turkish
Bath - all signs a
myth thus far -
Called at Mrs Wilborns
& told her I couldn't
stand the shoddy fixture
she had made me
for my head - then
to Dr Allen's I had
my teeth overlooked
and cleaned - it is
years since I have
had a cavity to fill —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes in pursuit of a Turkish bath, visits Mrs. Wilborn to complain about a fixture, and has her teeth cleaned by Dr. Allen.

entries.fullText:
Wrote 20 letters after
dinner about lecturing
matters & The Decade Meeting
Oct. 19 & 20th
Sister H. got a letter
from her Arthur saying
little Maude had been ill
& Dr. Jones gave her
Quinine—It is so
shocking that brother
D.R. will persist in
Allopathic Doctors.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote 20 letters about lecturing matters and The Decade Meeting. Her sister H. received a letter from Arthur saying that little Maude had been ill and was given Quinine by Dr. Jones. Susan expresses her shock that her brother D.R. will persist in Allopathic Doctors.

entries.fullText:
Looked over old clippings
& letters—Got Sister Annie's
letter written Wednesday—
Maude better—took cold
from kicking clothes off cold
night—
T. R. with George Baker
left for Greenwich near Lake
St Lawrence River, Lakes
Champlain & George
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony looked over old clippings and letters. She received a letter from her sister Annie saying that Maude was better but had taken a cold. T.R. and George Baker left for Greenwich near Lake St Lawrence River, Lakes Champlain & George.

entries.fullText:
Sister Mary and self
went to Plymouth Church
with Brother Aaron - M.B.
tried show the harmony between
Law and supernatural action -
Said God was over and above
his laws and could set them
aside — children may be
fed with such pap - but
not full fledged brains -
Eugene home - Aaron
visited Mr Bakers
entries.summaryText: Attended Plymouth Church with Sister Mary and Brother Aaron. M.B. spoke about the harmony between Law and supernatural action. Eugene went home and Aaron visited Mr Bakers.

entries.fullText:
Minister Bartlett
called-
entries.summaryText: Minister Bartlett called.

entries.fullText:
SEPTEMBER
13 Tuesday

Letter from Mrs L
C Dullard Ed. of the
New Revolution
offering to return
the paper to me
I at once replied
with guarantee
of $10,000 annually
I would undertake
to manage it again —
but never single handed
and alone
entries.summaryText: Mrs L C Dullard, editor of the New Revolution, offered to return the paper to me. I replied with a guarantee of $10,000 annually and that I would undertake to manage it again, but never single handed and alone.

entries.fullText:
Got notice of
Trustee Meeting
of [Rev.?] Association
for tomorrow 3 P.M.
Ordered Carriage
at door at 2.30 -
and walked up to
drive at Mrs Baker
Mrs Sackett there too
Got back to 7 Madison
St - found note from Mrs
Stanton advising me
to keep out of it - so
gave up and sent off carriage
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives notice of a Trustee Meeting and attends a drive at Mrs. Baker's house. She later receives a note from Mrs. Stanton advising her to stay out of it and sends off the carriage.

entries.fullText:
Took a ride
with Dr Allen
out Buffalo Road
and past Old Farm
— In getting out
of carriage after
arriving home - foot
slipped from stone
and fell with head
flat & hard on
Side Walk - pretty
blue & black for a
while - but no serious
hurt - Letter from [Lila?]
Browne - but no news -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony takes a ride with Dr. Allen and falls while getting out of the carriage, but is not seriously hurt. She receives a letter from [Lila?] Browne with no news.

entries.fullText:
At eve Mary
went round to
Frank Maliotts
& I called at
Amy Posts
later her if [of?] the
New Rev's prospect
of giving up the ghost
6th Anniversary of niece
Ann Eliza's funeral & 31st
of sister Gula's Marriage
entries.summaryText: Mary visited Frank Maliotts and Amy Posts. The New Rev's prospect of giving up the ghost was discussed. It was the 6th Anniversary of niece Ann Eliza's funeral & 31st of sister Gula's Marriage.

entries.fullText:
Frank Maliott &
wife—(Eliza
Combs of Battenville)
Dr Allen & wife
took tea at Sister
Hannah's—
George Baker &
Thomas Sherry
returned to day
Left Gula better
Got new button
glove kid boots at
Rhoades—my first
Button shoes—very nice
entries.summaryText: Frank Maliott, his wife Eliza Combs, Dr Allen and his wife had tea at Sister Hannah's. George Baker and Thomas Sherry returned. Gula was feeling better. Susan got new button glove kid boots at Rhoades, her first button shoes.

entries.fullText:
Democratic State
Con. Nominate P. T.
Hoffman for Gov —
Mary & self called
at Mr Collins' -
saw remarkable
fossil of woman's
chest & full breasts -
found in Rocky
Mountains -
Worked all day on old
Cash accounts - have
to make them strat,
make the figures tell the
truth —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the Democratic State Convention nominating P. T. Hoffman for Governor. She also mentions visiting Mr. Collins and seeing a remarkable fossil of a woman's chest and full breasts found in the Rocky Mountains. She spent the rest of the day working on old cash accounts.

entries.fullText:
Home- Bright & Beautiful
22 Thursday
Home - Bright & Deautiful
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes that it is a bright and beautiful day at home on September 22nd.

entries.fullText: Called at Hallowells, & [Miller's] - Mrs Wathey's there - Julia Ward Howe, in Woman's Journal puts out a call for a World Women's Peace Convention - too absurd for an enslaved class — disfranchised, penniless class. — freedom first —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Hallowells and Miller's, meets with Mrs. Wathey and Julia Ward Howe. Howe has put out a call for a World Women's Peace Convention, which Anthony finds too absurd for an enslaved and disfranchised class.
Susan B. Anthony writes a blank entry for September 24th.

entries.fullText:
Wrote Mrs Griffing—
sent ad bill of $49.40 to
O[?] A.C. Titch—he claims
of me $40.29—
Wrote 12 letters in all
Sister H. & Eugene came
home from Brockport
at 8.25 P.M.—had a
splendid visit—
Splendid rain all the A.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote a letter to Mrs. Griffing and sent an ad bill to O[?] A.C. Titch. She also wrote 12 letters and had a visit from Sister H. and Eugene.

entries.fullText:
delightful day—
received letter from
brother D. R. rejoicing
that I had refused
to take back the
Revolution—also
from Mrs. C. I. H.
Nichols saying she
could not attend
the Decade meeting—
Wrote Mrs Bullard recommending
Mrs Nichols as
office editor for The Rev—
and Mrs. E. B. Phelps &
a long chatty letter—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony received letters from her brother and Mrs. C. I. H. Nichols. She wrote a letter recommending Mrs. Nichols as office editor for The Revolution and a long chatty letter to Mrs. E. B. Phelps.

entries.fullText:
September
27 Tuesday

September
28 Wednesday
Sister Gula & niece Maggie
returned from Wash
Co. at 10 P.M. Sister
much improved—but
still far from well
entries.summaryText: Sister Gula and niece Maggie returned from Wash Co. at 10 P.M. Sister much improved—but still far from well.

entries.fullText:
Spent day mostly
in visiting with
Sister Gula—
Letter from Sister
Mary Luther with
$90 check for the
sewing machines—
also one from Mrs Bullard—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day visiting with Sister Gula and receives letters from Sister Mary Luther and Mrs Bullard regarding a $90 check for the sewing machines.

entries.fullText:
Very rainy—
niece Maggie
came down to spend
the day—
Took Cars
at 4 P.M. for New York [?]
[?] —found
Mr Sheldon on board
going to his Father
85—just got telegraph of his
illnes that A.M. & another
of death but a few minutes after
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's niece Maggie visits on a rainy day. Later, Susan takes a train to New York and meets Mr Sheldon, who just received news of his father's illness and death.

entries.fullText: Train late—went Dr Lozier's—cup of tea & lunch—then Mrs Phelps—all despair about the Decade meeting—then Alice Cary's—Phebe out—but Alice cordial—thence to Mrs Manchester's—just hours from three months in Europe then 4th St. Lib. & Julia Brown—Julia is wife of Geo. Bemis—G. F. Trains secretary—Married last July on her way to his Fathers in Boston—thence to Murray st found Studwell gone for a week—then to Tenafly by 4 P.M. train—Met Mrs S. & Hattie driving out—got in & rode an hour with them—Mr. H. B. S. Sen. gone to Washington
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to several places in the city, including Dr Lozier's, Alice Cary's, Mrs Manchester's, and 4th St. Lib. She met several people, including Mrs Phelps, Alice Cary, Julia Brown, and Mrs S. She also rode with Hattie and met Mrs Stanton's.

entries.fullText: Tenafly—N.J. Mrs Stanton's
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at Mrs Stanton's in Tenafly, NJ.

entries.fullText:
Went into New York
in A.M.—
Lunched at
T. Tiltons—Grandma
Morse there—
all on surface smooth—
Called at John P. Merritts—
Studwell out Revolution
Dined & slept at
Mr Curtiss'—all
seemed pleasant—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to New York, had lunch at T. Tiltons with Grandma Morse, called at John P. Merritts, and dined and slept at Mr Curtiss'.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Bullard took
me in carriage to
lunch with Mrs
Phelps—Mrs Williams
came—each gave
me a $5. to go to
Providence to get
Mrs Davis to throw
up the Decade—
left on 8 P.M.
Wretched Sleeping
Cars on Shore Line—
arrived at P. at 4 A.M. took carriage
to Mrs Davis—woke
her up—she came
to door—I got in
bed with her & not
a wink did she or
I sleep—She was
dreadfully distressed
at the proposition
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to lunch with Mrs Phelps and Mrs Williams, who each gave her $5 to go to Providence to get Mrs Davis to throw up the Decade. She arrived at Providence at 4 A.M. and woke up Mrs Davis, who was distressed at the proposition.

entries.fullText:
At 10.30—Mrs D.
telegraphed to New York
Decade must go on—
at 11 I sent a second
dispatch to Mrs Bullard
to make sure—at six
P.M.—Telegram came
that our messages were
too late & that notice of
abandonment was in Rev—
Mrs D. was almost frantic
& said it should be held—so
I took Stonington Line &
breakfasted at Tiltons—
then saw Tilton & Mrs
Bullard
entries.summaryText: Mrs. P. W. Davis telegraphed to New York about the Decade, Mrs D. sent a second dispatch to Mrs Bullard, telegram came that messages were too late and notice of abandonment was in Rev, Mrs D. was almost frantic, took Stonington Line and breakfasted at Tiltons, then saw Tilton and Mrs Bullard.

entries.fullText:
Arrived from
Providence—Saw
Mrs Bullard—got countermand
of abandonment on
City exchange
papers—& an item
in Associated Press
of the error—&
came out to Mrs
Stantons in P.M.
Got on board of Nyack
Express—had to get
off at Englewood—to
wait for next train—
None came to 8 P.M. then
hired a buggy at $1.50
& drove to Tenafly—
entries.summaryText: Arrived from Providence, saw Mrs Bullard, got countermand of abandonment on City exchange papers and an item in Associated Press of the error, came out to Mrs Stantons in P.M., got on board of Nyack Express, had to get off at Englewood to wait for next train, none came to 8 P.M. then hired a buggy at $1.50 and drove to Tenafly.

entries.fullText: Staid home all day-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stayed home all day.

entries.fullText:
Delightful day-
[Ny?] express ran off the track just below Englewood. I was on next train detained from 9 to 11 A.M. arrived at Mrs. Soyer's at 1 P.M.
Saw Miss Brown. Gave into her hands the newspaper notices for [?uade} meeting--didn't get over to Brooklyn.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a delightful day but was delayed due to a train accident near Englewood. She met with Miss Brown and gave her newspaper notices for a meeting, but didn't make it to Brooklyn.

entries.fullText:
Writing on True Republic
—The 4th Lead—The
reforms needed in
the home—Woman
absolute freedom—
Took walk at
dusk—the day
perfectly charming—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about True Republic, the reforms needed in the home, and woman's absolute freedom. She also mentions taking a walk at dusk.

entries.fullText:
Spent in New York
Got Pass on Erie R.R.
to Mansfield Ohio & return—
for E. C. S.—Put all
the Decade work in
the hands of Miss
E. C. Browne—
Called at Tiltons
Mrs T. leaves tomorrow
(Tuesday) for Marietta
Ohio to spend a month
Saw Mumford
Mrs. S. lecture agent—
also Gertine my agent.
Neither seem to have
done anything to help us
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day in New York, gets a pass for E. C. S. to Mansfield Ohio, and puts all the Decade work in the hands of Miss E. C. Browne. She also visits the Tiltons, who are leaving for Marietta Ohio, and meets with Mumford, Mrs. S., and Gertine, but none of them seem to have done anything to help her cause.

entries.fullText:
Wrote all
day on the government
branch of true republic
took ride at dusk
Bob & Hattie drivers
Letter from T. B.
Pugh about lecture in
Star Course in February
One from Sister Mary
Wrote Mrs Mary A.
Livermore congratulation
on reception by & action
the Massachusetts Republican
Convention—
Heavy rain all
the night
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about writing all day on the government branch of true republic, taking a ride at dusk, receiving letters from T. B. Pugh and Sister Mary, and writing a congratulatory letter to Mrs Mary A. Livermore on her reception by and action of the Massachusetts Republican Convention. She also mentions a heavy rain all night.

entries.fullText:
writing writing
beautiful day
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about writing on a beautiful day.

entries.fullText: Tenafly—

Tenafly—N.J.
Mrs S. & self
wrote & worked
up to 3 P.M.
then dinner &
she started for
Washington at
5 P.M. in carriage
Mr Sisson taking her
to Jersey City—20
miles to take night
Express—
Hattie & self
took a walk—then
went to my room &
to bed—perfectly
tired out—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs. S. wrote and worked until 3 P.M. before Mrs. S. left for Washington at 5 P.M. in a carriage. Hattie and Susan took a walk and then went to bed tired out.

entries.fullText: Went into City on 8.30 train & over to Brooklyn [& staid all night] with Mrs Davis & back to Dr Loziers & staid all night —Miss Brown had sent invitations to every body & done every thing up all right Mrs Stanton gave her "Marriage and Divorce" in Washington D.C. this evening—good audience—
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to the city and Brooklyn, stayed with Mrs. Davis and Dr. Loziers, attended a lecture by Mrs. Stanton in Washington D.C. and had a good audience.

entries.fullText: Went back to Tenafly on four P.M. train—Mrs. Stanton arrived about 8 evening—reported good times—Sat up until after 10 writing resolutions for the Decade meeting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony returned to Tenafly, Mrs. Stanton arrived and reported good times, and they wrote resolutions for the Decade meeting until after 10 PM.

entries.fullText:
Ground out
the resolutions
and took the
4.30 P.M. train
to New York—found
Mrs. M. C. Wright
at the James with
Mrs. P. W. Davis—a
great jam at Hotel
because of Unitarian
Convention.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took the train to New York and met with Mrs. M. C. Wright and Mrs. P. W. Davis at the James hotel.

entries.fullText:
Second Decade
reception at the
St James Hotel
Lucretia Mott—
Sarah Pugh, Mrs Stanton,
Olympia Brown, Mrs
Adelle Hazlett came—
The rain poured
Still nearly two hundred
called between 3 & 5 P.M.
—some 30 or 40 dined—
two colored women one
dressed in Quaker style
—the other a teacher in
City school—salary $1300.
name Tompkins—
Had preliminary meeting
in my room 17—Mott, Wright,
Pugh, Stanton, Davis, Hazlett,
Tilton, Bullard—a good deal
of feeling[?] about say "sole & absolute
right over her own person"
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the Second Decade reception at the St James Hotel and met with several women, including Lucretia Mott and Sarah Pugh. She also had a preliminary meeting with several people in her room, where they discussed the idea of a woman's 'sole & absolute right over her own person'.

entries.fullText:
Second Decade Celebration
of National Con -
at Worcester in 1850 -
at Apollo Hall
Corner 28th St and Broadway
Good attendance in A.M.
P.M. Davis - Pres -
Lucretia Mott spoke well
Mrs. Stanton - Olympia
Brown - Mrs Blake - &
self - I spoke on not
aligning ourselves to any
party till it openly declared
itself for Woman Suffrage
We should use both but
allow neither to use us.
entries.summaryText: Attended Second Decade Celebration of National Con in Worcester, where P.M. Davis, Lucretia Mott, Mrs. Stanton, Olympia Brown, Mrs. Blake, and Susan B. Anthony spoke on women's suffrage.

entries.fullText:
N. Bartholomew -
arrived at 1 P.M.
met Richard Merritt
& wife & 3 children of
Battle Creek Mich -
going to Painsville Ohio
to see the sister - Phebe
H. Merritt Stickney -
Mr B. at Depot -
Hon. Mr. Williams
introduced me - about
200 people present -
had one half gross
receipts - $41.50 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Dunkirk, met with N. Bartholomew, and gave a speech to about 200 people, earning $41.50 in receipts.

entries.fullText:
Stopped at Wm. H. Tews
married Mrs Smith - formerly
of Medina - widow in Treasury
Department at Washington
seven years - Mrs M. Guerley Tew
Mrs. A. F. Allen called
Mr. M. P. Dailey
Mrs. N. S. Flint
Fairbault, Minnesota
Levi Nutting - Lecture Com.
John W Griggs of Fairbault
Heavy rain come on
just at dusk - still
a fine audience of
200 present - Spoke much
more freely than at Dunkirk
one half gross receipts $50.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stopped at Wm. H. Tews and met several people including Mrs. Smith, Mrs. Guerley Tew, Mrs. A. F. Allen, Mr. M. P. Dailey, Mrs. N. S. Flint, Levi Nutting, and John W Griggs. She spoke to an audience of 200 people in Fairbault, Minnesota and earned half of the gross receipts of $50.

entries.fullText:
Took Chautauqua Lake
Steamer - Jamestown to
Mayville - at 8.30 A.M.
two hours at Brocton Depot -
J.L. Harris' Community here - just
saw Miss Jane T. WAring - the
business woman of the
community - then 1700 acres -
arrived at Mr M.C. Rice's
at 2. P.M. - found trunks
left at Prospect Station - sent
man over 4 miles - Had
splendid audience - 25 cts -
and entire net evening $28.
Mr Rice's wife was Rebecca
R. Crowe of Ohio - who
graduated from Antioch
& undertook to lecture in 1864
& here met Mr R. editor of
Republican & [?] [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took a steamer from Jamestown to Mayville and visited several locations including Brocton Depot, J.L. Harris' Community, and Mr. M.C. Rice's house. She spoke to a splendid audience and earned a net of $28. She also met Miss Jane T. Waring and Rebecca R. Crowe, who graduated from Antioch and undertook to lecture in 1864.

entries.fullText:
Miss Lydia [Hamness?], a
teacher called - also Mrs
A.B. Rice - took train
at 12 noon & arrived
at Rochester at 5.5 P.M.
found all well -
[Mr &] Mrs J.M. Clark
of North East Penn. came
over 15 miles to Westfield to
hear me speak - [?]
was Jane Brown of Jackson
Wash. Co. N.J.
Want me to call them
& speak -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives visitors and meets with supporters in Westfield, N.J.

entries.fullText:
Mary McLean Maxwell
& Cornelia McLean came
to dinner - Gula went
down town with us -
Cornelia staid all
night
T. R. went
home with George
& staid all night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony has dinner guests and spends time with friends in an unknown location.

entries.fullText: Cornelia McLean left for Auburn [went] heard Gen. Woodford - nominee for Gov - in Corinthian Hall - Maggie & boy Hary came down & staid all night
entries.summaryText: Cornelia McLean left for Auburn and heard Gen. Woodford speak at Corinthian Hall. Maggie and Hary stayed overnight.

entries.fullText: Maggie & George went to Plymouth Church with Aaron & T. H. - Eugene home - had good luck with his Fire Safe agency
entries.summaryText: Maggie and George went to Plymouth Church with Aaron and T. H. Eugene had good luck with his Fire Safe agency.

entries.fullText:
Left on 4 P. M.
Erie Train - Benj.
Fish on board -
Stand all night
at Corning - Brother
Aaron ordered Express
for Trunk - rained
when I got down
town took Knowles
carriage to Miss Larsons
- Monroe Depot - no trunk
- Knowles rushed to No. 7,
Madison St, for it -
Belmont N. Y. -
Surrogate Judge - Mr. Hatch
Miss Carrie E. Hatch - daughter
Miss Ellen Granby
north Blenheim
Schoharie Co, N. Y.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Erie to Belmont, stopping in Corning and Monroe Depot. She meets several people, including Miss Carrie E. Hatch and Miss Ellen Granby.

entries.fullText:
Belmont, All. Co., N. Y.
Mrs Wilkes Angel -
Left Corning at
6 A. M. met Mr. Angel
& niece on train, on
way to Belmont from
New York - the niece
friend Nellie Sheldon -
her sister Mrs Esther
Sheldon Granby - her mother
Mrs Cornelia Sheldon - a widow
- with Mrs Angel & Mrs
Granbys daughter of 11,
make the household - a
most delightful group -
Mr Angel introduced
me - spoke in Leavit
House - Small but
good audience -
delightful evening -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Belmont and meets Mrs. Wilkes Angel, Mr. Angel, and several members of the Sheldon family. She speaks at the Leavit House to a small but good audience.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. L. C. D'Antremont
thinks no hope of audience -
Belmont - spoke
Second time about
same audience -
100 in number - but
made one of my best
speeches -
night perfectly splendid
moonlight -
made one of my
best speeches - Mrs
Angel said it
must have been
special inspiration
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to an audience of 100 in Belmont and delivers one of her best speeches, despite Mrs. L. C. D'Antremont's doubts. Mrs. Angel suggests that it must have been special inspiration.

entries.dateText:
NOVEMBER
3 Thursday
Alfred All. Co. N. Y.
entries.fullText:
Mrs A. A. Allen -
rainy & cloudy &
sunshiny by turns -
left Belmont at 12.30
& arrived at Alfred at
1.26 - had good
audience in the
University Chapel of
200 - a great many
calls from teacher
& students
Met Mrs Stephens
Soneridge - sad Marriage
experience -
husband forsook her
took child - married
again - & she teaching
school - Didn't
make speech equal
to Belmont - Brain
worked so slowly & heavily
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to a good audience of 200 at the University Chapel in Alfred All. Co. and receives many calls from teachers and students. She meets Mrs. Stephens Soneridge, who shares her sad marriage experience. Susan feels that she did not deliver a speech equal to the one in Belmont due to her brain working slowly and heavily.

entries.fullText: Spoke a little to the students at chapel exercises - a lady student read chapter & made the prayer in a most dignified manner - asked Prof. Allen where there was a young man to match her - he said not in this college - except one other young lady - Prof. Hall of State Geological Looms Albany came - talked to boys - Emma Farrand of NY now married to Elkin gave me sad letter & made me sad visit. I bid her go forward.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke to students at chapel exercises and received a sad letter from Emma Farrand.

entries.dateText:
November
5 Saturday
Corning - Steuben Co. N.Y.
entries.fullText: Small meeting - every minister, lawyer doctor & teacher of town present - only 100 people - Henry A. Baleum Sup. Pub. Schools - The Silvester Group - English Humorists - asked for tickets - best slight of hand performer a married woman - had child Born at Dickinson Hotel - whole company had to wait her recovery - performed just three days before
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a small meeting in Corning and saw a married woman perform a slight of hand trick.

entries.fullText: Splendid day. Join Mrs Stanton on 605 train going West - Took train at 6 A.M. found Mrs Stanton at Hornellsville Breakfast table- went with her to Corning P[?] Station dined at Donner House & returned. Mrs. J.M. Chase of Randolph on board - Mr. McGuire- Proprietor of San Francisco Opera House also - arranged for Stanton & self to go over March or April - for one half gross receipts arrived at Owego at 10 P.M. Mrs Johnson, Mrs Brown & E. C. B. all at Depot to meet me
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony joins Mrs. Stanton on a train going West, dines at Donner House, and meets several people including Mr. McGuire, the Proprietor of San Francisco Opera House.

entries.fullText: Splendid Indian summer day. Day at Mrs. Browns Owego-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends a day at Mrs. Brown's in Owego on a splendid Indian summer day.

entries.fullText:
[Jack to New York]
Mrs Stanton - Chilicothe Ohio
entries.summaryText: Jack wrote to New York and Mrs. Stanton was in Chilicothe Ohio.

entries.fullText: Mrs Stanton - Oxford Ohio
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Stanton was in Oxford Ohio.

entries.fullText:
$100,
W.H. Gandy - [?] - at
Academy of Music
Ms Stanton - Greencastle
entries.summaryText: Meeting with W.H. Gandy and Ms Stanton at Academy of Music in Trenton N.J. and received $100.

entries.dateText:
NOVEMBER
14 Monday
Owego- Tioga Co. N. Y.
E.C. Downe manager
entries.fullText:
NOVEMBER
14 Monday
Owego- Tioga Co. N. Y.
E.C. Downe manager
entries.summaryText: Entry written on November 14, 1870 in Owego- Tioga Co. N. Y. mentioning E.C. Downe as the manager.

entries.dateText:
November
15 Tuesday
Binghampton N.Y.
E.C. Downe - Manager -
Mrs Stanton - Quincy, Ill -
entries.fullText:
November
15 Tuesday
Binghampton N.Y.
E.C. Downe - Manager -
Mrs Stanton - Quincy, Ill -
entries.summaryText: Entry written on November 15, 1870 in Binghampton N.Y. mentioning E.C. Downe as the manager and Mrs Stanton from Quincy, Ill.

entries.fullText: Found Sally Helly at Depot with Carriage & took me to Gleason's Cure, brought me my breakfast at 10- then chatted & left me to sleep- then Mrs Allen of Jamestown came to my room- Then Sally cooked & brought me my dinner at 4 P.M. nice steak &c- Had very small audience- Tom Beecher & wife present - Mrs Browne stopped at Hall owner's- Mr Wheeler -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Elmira, N.Y. and spends the day with Sally Helly, Mrs Allen, Tom Beecher, Mrs Browne, and Mr Wheeler. She had a small audience.

entries.fullText: E.P. Deitrick-[?] stopped at E.W. Cufron - good audience & pretty good of speech Took train from Elmira Hotel at 6 A.M.- [?] Browne went with me
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Williamsport, Pa- and gives a pretty good speech to a good audience. She took a train from Elmira Hotel with Sister Browne.

entries.fullText: Left Williamsport at 7:30 - arrived Elmira at noon - stopped at Mr. Wheeler's with Browne - wrote pile of letters northern part of state for meetings - Took the 6 evening Erie west - at Hornellsville found Judge Angel - who insisted I should spend Sunday at his house - we spent night at Wellsville & Saturday A.M. rode over to Cuba & found no meeting there for Saturday night.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Williamsport to Elmira, stopping at Mr. Wheeler's with Browne. She writes letters for meetings in the northern part of the state. She meets with Judge Angel in Hornellsville and spends the night in Wellsville. She rides over to Cuba on Saturday morning but finds no meeting there for Saturday night.

entries.fullText: Belmont - Saw Mr Freeland Loveridge & Mr at Cuba - very earnest & cordial - but returned with Angel in time for dinner - found a cordial reception by all -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Belmont and meets with Mr Freeland, Loveridge, and Mr at Cuba. She returns with Angel in time for dinner and finds a cordial reception by all.

entries.fullText:
Had delightful
day in my room
and visiting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a delightful day in her room and visiting on November 20th in Belmont.

entries.fullText:
Belmont for Cleveland
took Erie Train
at 10 A. M. -
Mrs Kelsey & Nellie
Hutchison - Blackwell
& Higginson
on board - also
Judge Whitehead
of N. Jersey - Evident
consternation with
the Americanites
Nellie & self went
to the Kenard House
- the rest to the Forest
City Hotel - then
Head Quarters -
Judge Brodwell at
Kenard
entries.summaryText: On November 21st, Susan B. Anthony traveled from Belmont to Cleveland on the Erie Train with several people, including Mrs. Kelsey, Nellie Hutchison, Blackwell, Higginson, and Judge Whitehead. She noted consternation with the Americanites. Nellie and Susan went to the Kenard House while the rest went to the Forest City Hotel. Judge Brodwell was at Kenard.

entries.fullText:
First Annual Mtg.
of the American W. S.
Association - Case Hill
- Kenard House -,
small audience
only 50 delegates -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the First Annual Meeting of the American W. S. Association in Cleveland, Ohio with only 50 delegates present.

entries.fullText:
no larger audience
Poor Show
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a poor show in Cleveland, Ohio with no larger audience present.

entries.fullText:
Mrs H. C. Washburn
stopped at Mrs C. F. Gouriet
Mrs. M Felsenheld
Thanksgiving night -
small audience -
- took just money
enough to pay me
my $100,
Mrs. H. B. Allaire
will work for Revolution
entries.summaryText: Mrs H. C. Washburn stopped at Mrs C. F. Gouriet. Mrs. M Felsenheld. Thanksgiving night - small audience - took just money enough to pay me my $100, Mrs. H. B. Allaire will work for Revolution

entries.fullText:
Called on [?]
Nevels - at [Filth?]
House - then
at Post Office
found letter from
Sister Mary - saying
Nephew Thomas [King?]
McLean was very
ill - attacked the 12th
written Monday 21st
Note by brother Aaron
saying he feared he might
have a run, of typhoid
[?] & with their terrible
precedent they were of
course very anxious
Telegraphed at Chicago -
got answer - no worse-
needn't come home -
entries.summaryText: Found letter from Sister Mary saying Nephew Thomas McLean was very ill. Aaron feared he might have a run of typhoid. Telegraphed at Chicago - got answer - no worse- needn't come home -

entries.fullText:
Chicago Ill -
at Mrs F. Jones
910 Prairie Avenue
went to Farwell
lower Hall at 2 P. M.
to Ill. State Ex. meeting -
found Lucy Stone there
- the Cleveland delegates
[?] - motion made
to annex to [?] Western [?] of
21 voted against - Lucy
made her charges against
Stanton & Anthony, National
[?] & Revolution & I
pricked them one by one
& carried the house
with me - She is too
small to be seen -
pitiable - pitiable -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting in Chicago and is able to carry the house with her against Lucy Stone's charges against Stanton and Anthony.

entries.fullText:
Went to M. E.
Church west side with
the Jones' - Pastor Mr
Fowler - fine sermon
- then to drive with
Mrs Corbin - author
of the Woman's Secret in
Rebecca - - then to
Farwell large Hall to
Temperance meeting &
spoke - a Mrs Robinson
the speaker - then home
with Col Fox to tea -
- then with Rebecca Mott
to call on Aunt A. Eliz
J. & then back to Mrs
Jones
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends church, goes to a temperance meeting, and visits with friends and family in Chicago.

entries.fullText:
No letter from brother
Aaron - about
Thomas King.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony did not receive a letter from her brother, but received news about Aaron and Thomas King.

entries.fullText:
[Detroit- Mich] Chicago
Left on 11.30
train & arrived at
Detroit 8.30
Found many
letters - but none
from house - so
hope Thomas King
is better -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony traveled from Chicago to Detroit and did not receive any letters from her house, but hopes that Thomas King is doing better.

entries.fullText: North Western W. S. A. Annual meeting meeting good through the three sessions.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the North Western W. S. A. Annual meeting in Detroit, Michigan.

entries.fullText: Left Detroit at 7:30 A.M. in company with [?] Brooks, wife & daughter for Rochester - who left at Hamilton - arrived Rochester at 8.30 found Nephew Thomas King McLean - very ill - but all very hopeful about him. - all the rest well - Gula & Aaron dreadfully worn with watching & anxiety Sister Mary sat up and I went to bed - - But T.K. had a very bad night - evidently a relapse - & hope sank again -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Detroit to Rochester and visits her nephew Thomas King McLean who is very ill.

entries.fullText: Went in to see Thomas King - very very much reduced - what ravages three weeks of disease can make - Sat up this night with sister Gula - Aaron went to bed until 4 A.M. then Gula & caught a nap on the sofa - Very hard night - sleeping but very little -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about visiting Thomas King who is very ill and spending a hard night with her sister Gula and Aaron.

entries.fullText: During the day T.K. became wandering a little at night still more - Talked of his hunting & Ellison and getting home to no 7 Mastison St. - Dr Summer came in Counsel with Dr Hurd - But all to no purpose I fear - sat up again Gula and Aaron dividing the night - A dreadful suffering night - The poor boy had never shut his eyes
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Thomas King's worsening condition and the doctors' counsel with no success. She also writes about spending another night with her sister Gula and Aaron and how Thomas King had never shut his eyes.

entries.fullText:
The dear
boy sank away & away
until 10.30 P.M. - when
the spirit passed out of the
body- His eyes scarcely
shut for an instant for
36 hours - Cruel fate
is all one can say - & yet
how much worse it might
have been -

Both doctors in A.M.
& evening - - Terrible to
see poor Aaron have
to give up his boy - the
hope of his life -

Undertaker [?] -
left Ed. Blackford
and Charlie Allen up -
and all went to bed
about 2 o'clock
entries.summaryText: The entry describes the death of a boy and the grief of his father Aaron.

entries.fullText:
Wrote letters to
a great many - Aaron
telegraphed - a
great many called -
T.K.s class [?]
seemed greatly shocked
and gave every attention
Young Eliz & [?] -
Geo. Perkins & others -
Oh why do not
their hearts break
Willie Webb &
Perkins sat up-
entries.summaryText: The entry describes writing letters, receiving visitors, and the grief of others over the death of the boy mentioned in the previous entry.

people: Dr. Henry R. & son Ed. and Dr. Leroy McLean
entries.fullText:
& son Ed. and Dr.
Leroy McLean came -
also Ellison & Mary
McLean & Maxwell -
Funeral at 2 P.M.
at Plymouth Church.
Bartlett & President
Anderson officiated -
- T. K's class all in a
body on one side of aisle
- large attendance
Took dinner at
[?] & then 9.45 took
train with Leroy and Henry
East - for New York.
entries.summaryText: Attended a funeral at Plymouth Church with Dr. Henry R. & son Ed. and Dr. Leroy McLean, Ellison & Mary McLean & Maxwell, Bartlett & President Anderson. T. K's class all in a body on one side of aisle. Took dinner at [?] & then 9.45 took train with Leroy and Henry East - for New York.

entries.fullText:
Exchange Hotel Mrs. Carrington.
About 50 people
in W.S. Court room.
Judge Underwood
present - Dr.
Sansteed took
me home with him -
- German -
Took the Lynchburg[?]
train so was
10 hours, instead
of 7 going -
R. D. Chesterman,
Ed Richmond
Equirer and Examiner
entries.summaryText: Stayed at Exchange Hotel Mrs. Carrington. About 50 people in W.S. Court room. Judge Underwood present. Dr. Sansteed took me home with him. Took the Lynchburg train so was 10 hours, instead of 7 going. Met R. D. Chesterman, Ed Richmond Equirer and Examiner.

entries.fullText: Mrs Bodeker took me to Hollywood Cemetery - Rebel dead there too - then to P. O. . to see Mrs Van [?] the P. M. and then to the Capitol- the House of Rep was in session - Clerk read invitation to my lecture - motion made to give me the Hall - lost by 38 to 19 - - 20 negro members - humiliating to the old Slave holders - Larger audience to night - seemed [?] pleased - Oh such need of work - but, no possibility of making meetings pay expenses
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Hollywood Cemetery and the Capitol in Richmond, where she is invited to give a lecture but the motion is lost by 38 to 19.

entries.fullText: Mrs Bodeker took me to call on Mrs Elizabeth Van Loos Mather - first class old time Slave holders mansion - then to Depot - at 11:15 - splendid dinner on Potomac Steamer enjoyed it hugely - arrived Mrs. Griffig at 7 p.m. - found Mrs Colburn & Mrs Lockwood there - slept with Mrs. G. again - Quaker Member of the Legislature - Mr Crenshaw - James C. Cowardrin [?] Local of Dispatch
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Richmond to Washington, where she visits Mrs. Elizabeth Van Loos Mather and enjoys a dinner on a Potomac Steamer.

entries.fullText:
Star Course -
Stopped A. E. Dickinson
- Susan & Mama, very
Nice - Lucretia Mott
called in P.M. - it rained
- Fine audience
Lucretia introduced
me in a happy manner.
Dr H. Longshore, Sarah
Pugh, the McClintocks
& others expressed great
delight with my speech
“The False Theory” - I was
So thankful that I did
so well as I did - not
my tippest toppest - but
still not a failure -
“Sue” remarked that
Anna had told her not to talk
to me about [?] - She was so
delighted that there [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks at the Star Course in Philadelphia and is introduced by Lucretia Mott. She receives positive feedback from the audience and meets with various individuals.

entries.fullText:
Before 8, A.M. dear
Lucretia called to
give me $20. toward
paying my Revolution
$10,000 - but little -
Still it expresses her
good will - Left
on 9.45 train for N.Y.
- met Mrs Hooker on
Ferry Boat. She will
do the work of the Washington
Con. - we talked
over every thing all night
until near 6 - she
went to N.J & I to
Tilton’s house - found
Ms T. with three youngest
children missing her mother
Florence is at Boarding
School - in New Jersey
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives a donation from Lucretia and travels to New York where she meets with Mrs. Hooker to discuss the Washington Convention.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Tilton at
her mothers & children too.
So didn't see her -
Generally stupid
time finding any
one - - called at
Maria Walkers - got
hot - she had telegram
of death of Mr Walkers
mother - - Found
[?] Brown & Julia
at Mrs Dr. Loziers
- got on board
Erie train for
Rochester - 7:20 P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her day in New York and Brooklyn, mentioning people and places she visited.

entries.fullText:
Rochester - arrived
via Erie R.R. about
11 A.M. - found all
well - Gula & Hannah
just starting to go to
Mr Bakers to dinner
- Aaron & Eugene
walked up at [?] P.M.
- I wrote letters
all the P.M. - Oh
how sad - what
a vacancy, what
a silence - no
T.K. to come in
from College - to
play piano - to sing -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Rochester and spends the day writing letters and reflecting on the absence of T.K.

entries.fullText:
December
16 Friday
Home

December
17 Saturday
Home

Sister Mary and self
went to church with
Aaron, Maggie, and George
Sad & lonely with no
T.K. by the Fathers side.
Mary and self called at
W. R. Hallowells to see
Wendell Phillips - met
me cordially - explained
the W. S. political absorption
of Massachusetts - Gov.
Clafflin - S. E. Sewell, Frank
Bird, Robinson, Slack
and Sanborn all behind
the Woman's Journal if the
women wouldn't [?]
W.P. - - Just as I had said
sold out to Republican Party.
W.P. spoke in Winston
Church. on Christianity a
force - a movement,
